The call memcmp(nn->nonce, new_nonce, new_nonce_len) can read new_nonce_len bytes from both nn->nonce and new_nonce. The function only contains mhd_assert() checks that new_nonce_len <= NONCE_STD_LEN(MAX_DIGEST) and other compile-time/runtime asserts; there is no unconditional runtime check that new_nonce_len <= sizeof(nn->nonce) or that new_nonce actually points to an object at least new_nonce_len bytes long. If mhd_assert is disabled or new_nonce_len is maliciously large, memcmp may access beyond the bounds of nn->nonce or beyond the buffer pointed to by new_nonce (e.g. new_nonce_len > sizeof(nn->nonce) or new_nonce shorter than new_nonce_len), violating Rule 21.17.
